C++ `std::regex` does not support the `\v` construct. You may match `\r\n\n` and match the line after it and capture into Group 1 with `(.+)`, and - if you want - match the line breaks, too:

    #include &lt;regex&gt;
    #include &lt;string&gt;
    #include &lt;iostream&gt;
    
    int main() {
    	std::regex reg{&quot;\r\r\n(.+)\r\n\r\n&quot;};
    	std::string text{&quot;AT+CGPADDR= 1\r\r\n+CGPADDR:\&quot;1 10.111.002.137\r\n\r\nOK\r\n&quot;};
    	std::smatch match;
    	if (regex_search(text, match, reg)) {
        	std::cout &lt;&lt; match.str(1); // =&gt; +CGPADDR:&quot;1 10.111.002.137
    	}
        return 0;
    }

See the [C++ demo][1].

Note the `.` won&#39;t match any line break chars, so it is safe to use a greedy `+` (*1 or more*) quantifier.


  [1]: https://ideone.com/DH1RsL

